\f3\fs20 \cf0 A few months into the 2020 presidential campaign, the environment is emerging as one of the most discussed issues on the campaign trail. Six in 10 Americans are concerned or alarmed about global warming, according to researchers at Yale and George Mason Universities, and presidential hopefuls are taking notice.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Candidates have rolled out significant 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  policy proposals, and although this week a panel of the Democratic National Committee denied a presidential debate devoted to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , CNN and MSNBC will host town halls on the topic in September.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As debate surrounding the issue has evolved, so have the words used to describe it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Years ago before scientists knew what human impact would mean for the planet, they called it "inadvertent 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  modification." Now, environmental activists and some lawmakers say the planet is in trouble, and they're calling it a crisis.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As knowledge and understanding of the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  have deepened, so has the desire to give the topic a more accurate label -- and possibly engage voters from both major political parties.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This spring when Spark Neuro, a company which monitors brain and nervous system activity to measure how people are feeling, tested words for environmental 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , "
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis" rose to the top. Gut reactions to "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " showed the term to be innocuous. "Global warming"was deemed alarmist. Neither term elicited emotional reactions from Democrats or Republicans. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis, however, "could strike a bipartisan chord as a more reasonable observation," said the survey results. "To reframe the issue is to engage unconvinced voters, and ... '
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis' may hit the sweet spot."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The words are a reflection of personal politics, said linguistic and political experts, but it is unclear whether 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  terminology equals action, specifically among the unconvinced.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I think the 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in terminology probably creates better headlines, but I don't think it is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  policy much," said Andrew Pieper, associate professor of political science at Kennesaw State University. "It is probably even hurting politicians because they have this huge incentive to avoid the language their opponents use."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Words matter, and what we say conveys our attitude toward what we are talking about, said Sarah Blackwell, professor of linguistics at the University of Georgia. "Very rarely are words neutral. They are typically positively or negatively nuanced in some way," she said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Inadvertent 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  modification" never really took off, for obvious reasons. Scientists would later use "global warming" to describe surface temperature increases due to rising levels of greenhouse gases. They used "climatic 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " or "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " to describe longterm 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in Earth's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , which include global warming.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 For decades, despite its limitations, "global warming" was the term of choice in popular culture. Then in 2002, Republican strategist Frank Luntz suggested President George W. Bush use only the term "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It was less ominous sounding, Luntz said. And it was a term supported by the scientific community, including NASA which uses the term "global 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " in communications.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But words weren't the only thing 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . In the 1990s, 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  policies had been largely bipartisan, said politicians.A decade later, those policies had become partisan issues and the words a candidate or lawmaker used to talk about them became part of their personal branding.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "We used to think of culture wars and identity politics as only being about gender mores and traditional family values, but as the parties have become more ideologically split, every policy debate is potentially identity politics," said Pieper of Kennesaw State.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "In Washington they argue over the semantics," said Jason Buelterman, mayor of Tybee Island. "All I can say is that from my perspective as a local official on a barrier island that is low to the sea, we have experienced the effects of sea level rise and we are dealing with it, regardless of what they do in Washington."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It's hard to say how "
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis" originated. Al Gore was already making references to a crisis when his 2006 documentary "An Inconvenient Truth" was released. Environmental advocacy groups were also attaching more urgency to the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  conversation by using words that would serve as a call to action. Earlier this year, Gore's 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Reality Project launched an online petition asking news organizations to make the switch.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In May, the Guardian updated its style guide to include "
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis" as the preferred term over "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But some local politicians say altering the course of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  will require much more than new terminology.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I don't need fancy talk," said state Rep. Al Williams, D-Midway, a self-proclaimed Gullah Geechee from coastal Georgia. "It is a crisis because unfortunately politics has become so divided and so partisan.We need to sit down in a bipartisan effort and get back to doing what we did and make sure we survive and leave something for the next generation."
