\f3\fs20 \cf0 Tim Pawlenty: "The weight of the evidence (on global warming) is that most of it, maybe all of it, is because of natural causes ... it's fair to say the science is in dispute."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Pawlenty, the former Minnesota governor who was briefly in the race for the 2012 GOP presidential nomination, made these comments to The Miami Herald.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 PolitiFact divided his statement into two parts:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 1) Evidence points toward 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  being primarily a natural, rather than manmade, phenomenon.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 2) The science about the causes of global 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is in dispute.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Based on our research, there is very little dispute in the scientific community, especially among 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  specialists, on whether 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is primarily caused by natural or manmade forces. The majority of scientists polled feel human activity is the primary driver of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Based on scientific studies, global warming over the past 50 years has been primarily driven by human activity.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Pawlenty's claims are both incorrect and misleading to the public, who may not be familiar with the science behind 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . It is not "fair to say the science is in dispute," as if there are good arguments on both sides. Rather, there is significant scientific consensus that human beings are contributing to global warming. We rated his statement False.
\f0\fs24 \
