\f3\fs20 \cf0 President Barack Obama used his recent trip to Alaska and about every other opportunity he s gotten to proclaim that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is the most important issue of our time. We re here today to discuss the challenge that will define the contours of this century more dramatically than any other that s the urgent and growing threat of a 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , he said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 While not all environmental scientists agree with the president, most of the mainstream media emphatically do. And they are the ones who will be grilling Republican candidates and not just the presidential candidates.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That means GOP office-seekers need to be informed about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  matters and ready with clear, evidence-backed answers. What are some of the key issues?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Is the earth warming? Well, it certainly has warmed since what was known as the Little Ice Age a cold period that lasted from about 1550 to 1850. There has been a gradual increase since about 1910, with a strong uptick between the mid-1970s and about 1997. Since then, global temperatures have been relatively flat.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But the flattening came after a significant warming trend. That means even a slight temperature increase in a given year allows the media to claim it is the warmest year on record, even if the 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is within the margin of error.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 While we don t know whether the warming trend will resume in the near future, we do know that almost all the global warming proponents never saw the flattening coming. They incorrectly predicted much warmer temperatures that have not occurred.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And now some 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists are predicting a multiyear cool-down, a mini-ice age, within the next decade or so that could raise further questions about the temperature trend.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Is Arctic ice melting? While in Alaska, the president visited Exit Glacier, which has been shrinking for decades. Yes, Arctic ice has been gradually declining but Antarctic ice has been growing.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 We know the rise-and-fall process has been going on naturally for millennia, without any help from mankind. What we don t know though many will say we do is whether the recent temperature increase is part of the natural variation that occurs about every 100,000 years or is caused by human activity.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Are humans to blame? Carbon dioxide has been increasing, and most 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists believe man is playing a role in that increase. But is carbon dioxide causing the warming?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As the Environmental Protection Agency shows, for the past 400,000 years, temperature levels and carbon dioxide levels have followed virtually identical tracks.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Can the U.S. solve the problem? Journalists will ask what Republican candidates intend to do about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The U.S. is responsible for about 14.5 percent of world carbon emissions, with China at 23.5 percent. When you re only 14.5 percent of the total, you have to make huge carbon reductions just to decrease total emissions by a fraction of a percent.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The good news, at least for conservative candidates, is that the public ranks cutting carbon emissions very low among their priorities for the upcoming election.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Even so, the environment, and specifically 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , is one of the media s biggest issues, and they are likely to make it very hot for Republican candidates who don t know the facts or give them politically incorrect answers.
