\f3\fs20 \cf0 Former President Barack Obama called 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  an "existential issue" and emphasized the importance of equity in solving sustainability and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  problems during a Wednesday morning appearance at a green building conference in Atlanta.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Thousands of people packed the Georgia World Congress Center to hear Obama at the annual Greenbuild International Conference and Expo.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 His appearance coincided with the Democratic presidential debate taking place in Atlanta on Wednesday night. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  has become one of the major issues along the campaign trail for the 2020 Election. Ten of the candidates participated in a Sept. 4 CNN-sponsored town hall about the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis, and the topic has come up often during debates.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Obama steered clear of political talk during his hourlong conversation with Mahesh Ramanujam, president and CEO of the U.S. Green Building Council, focusing instead on a range of issues from social equity to training the next generation of leaders. He spoke about the urgency of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and referenced his work in finalizing the Paris Accord -- the voluntary, nonbinding pledge from almost 200 parties to reduce their carbon emissions over time -- from which the Trump administration announced it would formally withdraw earlier this month.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The former president also urged the audience to think about equity in solving issues of sustainability--connecting global economic inequality with 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . "The reason I say those two things are connected is that it is hard to figure out how we solve sustainability issues and deal with 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  if you also have huge gaps in wealth and opportunity and education ... as wealth gets more and more concentrated and more and more energy is used up by the few, the many become resentful and it undermines our sense of politics and a sense of community. It is hard for us then to mobilize the body politic around taking collective action," he said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Growing up in Hawaii gave him a certain mindfulness about limited resources and land, which even as a child he could appreciate and recognize the need to preserve, he said. Those are values he instilled in his own children, who have a developed a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  consciousness typical of their generation. Sasha, for example, once banned the family from using plastic bottles, he said. To help move the next generation into effective leadership, Obama said programming from the Obama Foundation centers on training young people to use strategies and tactics that result in action.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the fight against 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , it is important, he said, to be sure our values and actions are in alignment. "If we say our children or the next generation are the most important thing, then we have to act in accordance with those values," he said. "Any society where how we live strays too far from what we say we believe is going to have problems, and currently there is more divergence than I would like."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 While everyone can do their part individually to address 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  concerns, there are some issues that must be dealt with collectively, Obama said.
