\f3\fs20 \cf0 Five years ago, the National Audubon Society released an alarming study forecasting danger from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  for 314 bird species that occur in North America. Several of them, the report said, likely will be extinct by 2080.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Dozens of the species cited in the study occur in Georgia, including the bald eagle, osprey, whip-poor-will, scarlet tanager, wild turkey, orchard oriole, wood thrush, hairy woodpecker, nuthatches, sparrows, several warbler species and others.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Based on U.N. 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  projections and hundreds of thousands of hours of "citizen-science" observations, including Christmas Bird Counts, the Audubon study predicted that if 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  continues at its expected rate, it likely will force vulnerable birds into smaller spaces or drive them to find new places to live, feed and nest over the next 65 years. As a
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 result, many bird populations likely will be decimated, including extinction for some species.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Now, Audubon is conducting a nationwide pilot program, called 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Watch, to test and fine-tune the predictions. The Atlanta Audubon Society (AAS) is part of the project, which began two years ago and is designed to help researchers determine if birds are shifting their ranges, habitats and other behaviors in response to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In Atlanta, 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Watch volunteers are focusing on the Eastern bluebird and brown-headed, white-breasted and red-breasted nuthatches, said Adam Betuel, AAS's conservation director. Between now and Feb. 15, volunteers will conduct one
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 dozen five-minute point counts in assigned areas to record all bluebirds and nuthatches seen or heard.
