\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A few leaked e-mails can't 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  the consensus of science.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 By Alan I. Leshner
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Don't be fooled about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science. In April, 1994 --- long after scientists had clearly demonstrated the addictive quality and devastating health impacts of cigarette smoking --- seven chief executives of major tobacco companies denied the evidence, swearing under oath that nicotine was not addictive.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Now, the American public is again being subjected to those kinds of denials, this time about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . While Sarah Palin wrote that she did not deny the "reality of some 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," she distorted the scientific evidence that Earth's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , largely as a result of human behaviors. She also badly confused the concepts of daily weather 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and long-term 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  trends when she wrote that "while we recognize the occurrence of these natural, cyclical environmental trends, we can't say with assurance that man's activities cause weather 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ." Her statement inaccurately suggests that short-term weather fluctuations must be consistent with long-term 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  patterns. And it is the long-term patterns that are a cause for concern.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\b\fs20 \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science is clear: The concentration of atmospheric carbon dioxide --- derived mostly from the human activities of fossil-fuel burning and deforestation --- stands at 389 parts per million. We know from studying ancient Antarctic ice cores that this concentration is higher than it has been for at least the past 650,000 years. Exhaustive measurements tell us that atmospheric carbon dioxide is rising by 2 ppm every year and that the global temperature has increased by about 1.1 degrees Fahrenheit over the past century. Multiple lines of other evidence, including reliable thermometer readings since the 1880s, reveal a clear warming trend. The broader impacts of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  range from rapidly melting glaciers and rising sea levels to shifts in species ranges.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 Already, sea levels are estimated to rise by 1 to 2 meters by the end of this century. Some scientists have said that average temperatures could jump by as much as 4 degrees Fahrenheit if the atmospheric carbon dioxide level reaches 450 ppm. We may face even more dangerous impacts at 550 ppm, and above that level, devastating events. U.S. crop productivity would be affected, and European communities might suffer increased fatalities because of intensely hot summers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Doubters insist that the Earth is not warming. This is in stark contrast to the consensus of 18 of the world's most respected scientific organizations, who stated in an Oct. 21 letter to the U.S. Senate that human-induced 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is real. Doubters also make selective use of evidence, noting that the warming of the late 1990s did not persist from 2001 to 2008, while ignoring the fact that the first decade of the 21st century looks like it will be the warmest one on record.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 None of these tactics 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  the clear consensus of a vast majority of scientists, who agree that the Earth is warming as greenhouse gas levels rise. The public and policy-makers should not be confused by a few private e-mails that are being selectively publicized and, in any case, remain irrelevant to the broad body of diverse evidence on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Selected language in the messages has been interpreted by some to suggest unethical actions such as data manipulation or suppression. To be sure, investigations are appropriate whenever questions are raised regarding the transparency and rigor of the scientific process or the integrity of individual scientists. But it is wrong to suggest that apparently stolen e-mails, deployed on the eve of the Copenhagen 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  summit, somehow refute a century of evidence based on thousands of studies.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Palin also errs by claiming that America can't afford to reduce greenhouse gases. The highly regarded Stern Commission revealed that inaction could cost us the equivalent of between 5 percent and 20 percent of global gross domestic product per year. In contrast, the price of slowing emissions was estimated to be 1 percent of GDP. China, meanwhile, reportedly is investing heavily in clean energy technologies.
\f0\fs24 \

