\f3\fs20 \cf0 Not only is the faith community not active enough in addressing environmental issues, in many cases people of faith have actively resisted the notion that we are facing real and even life-threatening environmental issues. If you take just one issue, I have frequently heard good people say, "I just don't believe in global warming." That's a little like saying "I just don't believe the earth is round." Whether we believe in it or not, scientific facts are now demonstrating that global warming is real, and that human beings (particularly through overconsumption and waste) have contributed to it. Another mistake faith communities have made is thinking this is a political issue rather than the issue of environmental stewardship that it is. Human beings were given dominion over the earth because God thought we were smart enough to use our world's resources wisely and well. Yet the serious global environmental issues we are facing reflect not wisdom, but greed and pride. As for everyone doing their (even small) part, we have to start somewhere. But at the same time we also need a bigger movement, backed by funding from corporations and government, and talked about and worked on in every community (workplace, church, and neighborhood) to make real 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in lifestyle that can reverse the direction we are heading.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---The Rev. Kathy McDowell, Peachtree Corners Christian Church pastor
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It isn't the church's responsibility to address environmental issues. As individual Christians we are to be good and faithful caretakers of all that God has given us (that includes the earth). But we do not need to be overly concerned about the "dire" nature of these environmental issues because God has promised, "While the earth remains, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat, winter and summer, and day and night shall not cease" (Genesis 8:22).
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Too many churches today are neglecting the preaching of Christ crucified in favor of participation in ever-increasing social and political causes. The recent partnership between Ted Turner with the ELCA, LC-MS, and UMC to fight malaria in Africa is a perfect example. Fighting malaria and addressing environmental issues are certainly noble causes, but the church isn't fulfilling its calling now! True Christian teaching is being watered down, and we are failing to carry out Christ's command to teach "them to observe all things that I have commanded you" (Matthew 28:20). The result of not teaching the whole counsel of God faithfully is this: "The time will come when they will not endure sound doctrine, but according to their own desires, because they have itching ears, they will heap up for themselves teachers; and they will turn their ears away from the truth" (2 Timothy 4:3-4). This is readily apparent within many churches right now! The church needs to return to its God-given directive of preaching the message of Christ crucified and all things He has commanded.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---The Rev. Nathanael Mayhew, Zion Lutheran Church pastor
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The clergy community has an obligation to point people in the right direction and to underscore the gift of God's earth, as reflected in Psalm 136: "Give thanks unto the Lord for He is good. His mercy and His love are always with us. The harmony of nature reveals God's wisdom ..." We as ministers, priests and rabbis continue to remind and instruct our congregants through the ancient wisdom of the Bible. People who hear the message must then turn the message into action. Each individual must ask, "What have I done to reduce pollution, to recycle, or to promote the harmony of nature, to maintain our beloved earth?"
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---Rabbi Ronald Bluming, Temple Beth David
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Bible teaches us that the Church's primary focus must be the preaching of the Word (2 Timothy 4:2). As we consider the life and ministry of Jesus it quickly becomes clear that He never deviated from His mission but kept the main thing the main thing. The Church is here to save men, not save the planet, to warn others about the fires of hell, not global warming and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , and that Jesus died on the cross to cleanse us from the pollution of sin, not CO2 emissions. As we consider the worth of a human soul in contrast with importance of these current "hot" political topics, a verse comes to mind in Mark 8:36, "For what will it profit a man if he gains the whole world, and loses his own soul?"
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---Pastor Mark Byrd, Calvary Chapel
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I think we have a pretty spotty record on this one. God gave us the earth and expects us to be a good steward of all he has entrusted to us. We can see all around us the evidence of our sins of commission and omission in caring for God's creation. As pastors we have often failed to call for repentance and restoration in this and other areas. I don't think the issue is so much liberal vs. conservative or exploiters vs. tree huggers. I think the issue relates more to personal awareness of impact and responsibility. There are so many things we can do which will aggregate into big 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . We are indeed called to be good stewards of all that God has entrusted to us. We need to do a better job as faith communities of sharing this as part of God's word.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---The Rev. Keith Lawder, Simpsonwood United Methodist Church associate pastor
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I believe it was Dr. Jacob Bronowski in the PBS documentary "The Ascent of Man" who said that human beings were not, like other animals, creatures who live in the landscape, but are in fact creators of the landscape. As such, we have special responsibilities as stewards of Creation. The Book of Genesis in the Bible is clear on this point: Our dominion over Creation, such as it is, comes with awesome responsibilities.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But nature is very subtle, and it is hard to know just what exactly to do. One example:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the late thirties a Swiss chemist named Paul Muller discovered the insecticide properties of DDT. DDT is extremely effective in destroying the insect-borne diseases of typhus and malaria. Unfortunately, it is a poison that tends to stay in animal fatty tissue.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Forty six years ago Rachel Carson's "Silent Spring" pointed out the dangers of DDT so effectively that the pesticide was widely banned by developed countries. Many environmentalists wanted to ban it in tropical countries, too. But the mosquitoes that DDT kills so effectively carry the malaria which could take millions of lives if the insecticide is abruptly discontinued. So only very careful thinking, not simplistic solutions driven by political ideology, is called for to solve this and other environmental problems.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---Rabbi Richard Baroff, Guardians of the Torah
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Any understanding of God's will for our lives must take caring for creation into account. The first "calling" found in Scripture includes God's charge for us to be good stewards of His creation. Why? Creation sustains life, has a way of putting us in our place and is the greatest witness to a Creator. Living in our urban jungles, it can be easy to forget the serious responsibility of God's call for us to be good stewards of creation. As stewards, we must do better in our advocacy of environmental issues and our participation in environment-saving practices. If we don't do better, future generations will suffer because we failed "on our watch." If we don't do better, the greatest witness to God will no longer testify. If we don't do better, we run the risk of forgetting that we are the created, not the Creator. The better we do, the better chance there is of a world abounding with Psalm 8 moments, and what a world that would be. "When I consider your heavens, the works of your hands, the moon and the stars which you have set in place, who are mere mortals that you are mindful of us, human beings that you care for us? ... Lord, our Lord, how majestic is your name in all the earth!"
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---The Rev. Drew Gaylor, Gwinnett Church of Christ minister
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 There is a great quote attributed to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. It's something like: the church has the option of being the thermostat of the world or the thermometer, meaning we, the church, can be the source of 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  or, as a thermometer, simply record ideas and principles that arise out of popular opinion.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 We have missed the opportunity to be the "thermostat" on environmental issues, often dubbing such groundbreaking issues as too radical for the church. But we are beginning to act as a thermometer, measuring and judging those environmental movements already at work.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I do not believe that we are active enough in addressing environmental issues, though, as a vehicle is judged Christian not according to its emissions or gas consumption, but according to the presence or absence of a fish symbol. We are concerned with creation, but too often only as a theological issue to be dealt with by a war on Darwinism. We forget that regardless of how God created our world, we are left with responsibility over it --- a responsibility that we have dealt with selfishly, without regard for fellow human beings. God offers guidance leading us to live responsibly on this earth God created today. While I wish the church had spoken up earlier, I am grateful that we are beginning to speak up now.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---The Rev. Joe Evans, Good Shepherd Presbyterian Church associate pastor
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Probably not. We can get pretty lazy on that stuff. However, the church has a vested interest in environmentalism more than any other organization because followers of Jesus believe that Jesus came to redeem all of creation. We believe God called creation "good." We probably don't stress that enough. When we do, though, it needs to be geniune. It's sort of sad to see "being green" as trendy right now, and I wonder how much of it is slick marketing rather than genuine concern for the environment. So when faith communities do step forward on the environmental issues, it needs to be centered on authentic concern for all of God's creation. People that love God should love earth more than anyone else on the planet. That just makes sense.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 --- The Rev. Carter McInnis, Church of the Way lead pastor
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 No, I think that all faith communities have tremendous potential to help coach us to steward well God's beautiful creation. We seem to spend more time teaching stewardship of finances and physical health than we do teaching the stewardship of the world we are blessed to live in. My prayer is that God would give us a Holy Passion to be better stewards of water, air, land and wildlife and respect each as a part of God's creation to sustain human life.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ---The Rev. Steve Wood, Mount Pisgah UMC senior pastor
