\f3\fs20 \cf0 WASSAW SOUND ESTUARY, GA.--The fall of 2013 should have been a blessing for Georgia shrimpers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A bacterial infection had wiped out the Asian shrimp farms that drove many Americans out of business. Early sampling at the time indicated a bumper crop of white shrimp on the way. Many poured money into fixing up their boats in preparation for long, rewarding days on the water.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But the nets came up empty.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "They were gone," recalled Marc Frischer, a microbiologist at the University of Georgia's Skidaway Institute of Oceanography near Savannah. "There were no shrimp."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Wildlife officials and shrimpers clashed over the cause of the sudden die-off. What followed was years of research by a team of scientists across the South.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The results of those efforts show how 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  are likely impacting Georgia's coastal ecosystems, and those who depend on them to make a living.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I'm 100% a believer," said Richard Puterbaugh, president of the Georgia Shrimp Association. "I had a front-row seat for 45 years. I've seen the 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Shrimping has, historically, been vital to the food, culture and economy of the Georgia coast. Today, it makes up a tiny fraction of state's gross domestic product. Still, this shrinking industry supports hundreds of jobs and brings in millions of dollars.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As shrimpers follow their crop north into colder waters, and a new shrimp parasite reaches epidemic proportions, scientists are investigating how 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  could influence the future of shrimp and shrimping in the Southeast.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Temperature, current, rain flow -- all of those are related to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , and all of those play very critical roles in the complicated biology and ecology of the system," said Frischer. "Not just for shrimp, for everything."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 After the shrimp disappeared in 2013, the government declared a fishery disaster.Officials cited extreme rainfall that likely prevented shrimp larvae, hatched offshore in the ocean, from returning to the estuaries where they grow to maturity.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But shrimpers were unconvinced. They blamed black gill, a mysterious affliction that was becoming increasingly prevalent in shrimp harvested off the Georgia coast. Named for the immune response that darkens the crustacean's gills, black gill is harmless to humans who eat the shrimp and does not affect taste. But it weakens the animal, making it more vulnerable to predators and less likely to survive.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A reporter for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution recently joined Frischer and his colleagues aboard the Research Vessel Savannah to study black gill in the Wassaw Sound Estuary. The intention of the annual stakeholder cruise is to bring together shrimpers, academics and wildlife officials to share research and observations.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Black gill remains a source of tension--particularly between shrimpers, who say it is devastating their crop, and wildlife managers, who say they have no evidence of that.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Mike Younce of Brunswick was a commercial shrimper for two decades. He said he first started noticing black gill, and its effect on shrimp, in the late '90s.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The shrimp that didn't have the black gill, they would be lively," Younce said. "They would be jumping when they hit the deck."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The shrimp with darkened gills, however, were small and sickly, their shells soft.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "They were out of gumption," said Younce. "Like they were wore out."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Solving the
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 mystery of black gill
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Scientists knew black gill was caused by an immune response in the shrimp's body, but to what? Where did it come from, and why was it spreading?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Frustration over the failed 2013 harvest pushed the Georgia Sea Grant, part of a federal program based at colleges and universities, to prioritize funding for black gill research.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Since then, scientists have established that the black gill seen in Georgia shrimp is caused by a ciliate -- a single-celled organism that attaches itself to the animal's gills. Ciliates are fairly common hitchhikers on shrimp, but they had never been known to cause problems.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "There aren't actually that many experts in the world that work on ciliate parasites of crustaceans," Frischer said. "We showed (our research) to all of them, around the world, and nobody had seen anything like that before."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It took years of collecting, dissecting and studying shrimp, but, in 2019, scientists were finally able to put a name to the scourge: A brand new species of ciliate they called Hyalophysa lynni after a well-known marine biologist, Denis Lynn, who died in 2018.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Much work remains to be done in order to determine how, exactly, the parasite feeds and spreads. In the meantime, it has reached epidemic proportions off the coast of Georgia and South Carolina, and appears to be moving into the Gulf of Mexico and as far north as the Chesapeake Bay.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Stephen Landers, the protozoologist at Troy University in Alabama who identified Hyalophysa lynni, said the species "broke the mold" of how this type of ciliate was expected to behave.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Parasite species don't just evolve in 50 years," Landers said. "This is something that's been on the planet for millions of years. Now, at this time, in this part of the world, for whatever reason, it's thriving."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Experts say there appears to be a strong correlation between black gill and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  conditions. While correlation does not equal causation, this theory is supported by experiments in the lab on the shrimp themselves.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In one study, 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  water temperature by just two degrees had a huge impact on mortality rates for shrimp exposed to the parasite: a difference of up to 70%.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Coastal water temperatures in Georgia have increased by nearly five degrees over the past four decades, according to data collected by the state. Even with seasonal variation, the increasing trend is clear. Using a commonly employed statistical test developed by U.S. government scientists, the AJC concluded that such a consistent and steady increase is unlikely to arise randomly.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Most infectious disease in aquatic animals is worse with rising temperatures," said Eddie Leonard, a marine biologist with the Georgia Department of Natural Resources. "I don't think it's unlikely that there is some relationship between global temperature and infection rates, including for black gill."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Warming waters, warming planet
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In order to understand what's happening to Georgia's coast, it's important to understand why global temperatures are -- on average -- rising.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Earth's atmosphere is so thin, compared to the planet's size, that it has been compared to the parchment skin of an onion. Most of the ultrathin layer that supports life is made up of nitrogen (78%), oxygen (20.9%) and argon (0.9%).
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Less than 0.05% of the atmosphere is made up of greenhouse gases, like carbon dioxide and methane. These gases absorb and then reemit heat from the sun to keep the planet at a livable temperature. Because these gases make up such a small proportion of the atmosphere but play such a large role in regulating Earth's surface temperature, human activity like burning fossil fuels can and does have a global impact.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Before the industrial revolution, carbon dioxide levels were about 280 parts per million. Today, they have surpassed 400 ppm -- the highest in at least 800,000 years.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And just as a two-degree temperature shift can mean life or death for a shrimp, 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  to global temperature that appear slight can have far-reaching consequences.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Earlier this year, scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies announced global temperatures in 2018 were 1.5 degrees Fahrenheit warmer than the "baseline" period of 1951 to 1980. The past five years are, collectively, the warmest in the modern record, they said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "2018 is yet again an extremely warm year on top of a long-term global warming trend," GISS Director Gavin Schmidt said in a statement at the time. "The impacts of long-term global warming are already being felt -- in coastal flooding, heat waves, intense precipitation and ecosystem 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Most excess heat and greenhouse gases are absorbed by the world's oceans, which are growing warmer and more acidic as a result. Ice sheets are melting, and sea levels are rising. Major currents, like the Gulf Stream, which brings warm water up from the tropics past Georgia on its way to the North Atlantic, are slowing and possibly shifting course.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 These and other 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  are affecting 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and weather systems around the globe. On Georgia's coast, that includes 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in water temperature, salinity and oxygen levels in the estuaries that are home to countless species, including shrimp.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "For me, 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is not about polar bears or the year 2080 -- it is about issues affecting the daily lives of all of us right now," said Marshall Shepherd, director of the Atmospheric Sciences Program at UGA. "This is one of them. We eat shrimp, and hardworking people rely on them for their livelihood."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Disappearing way of life
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Georgia's shoreline once teemed with shrimp boats, mostly small, family-owned wooden trawlers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "It looked like a city out there," said Puterbaugh of the Georgia Shrimp Association. "Now, if you see 10 boats it's crowded. That's how much it's 
\f1\i\b \ul changed
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In 1979, there were 1,471 licensed shrimp boats. Last year, the state issued permits to just 258. Some of the same families remain in the business, but most of the small crafts have been replaced by larger, more expensive boats, and about a third of licenses were given to non-Georgia residents.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The decline of the local shrimp industry is largely due to economic factors. The cost of maintaining and fueling a boat is high, and dock prices for wild caught shrimp are comparatively low. Consumers have grown accustomed to paying bargain prices for cheap farmed shrimp, mostly imported from Asia.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But some say the shrimp crop has also become more unreliable because of black gill.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "This is not a minor problem," said Mike Sullivan, who has been shrimping off the Georgia coast for 52 years, since he was 14. "This problem is killing millions of pounds of harvestable shrimp."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Georgia wildlife officials are cautious in their assessment of black gill's impact on the industry.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I don't think it's good, but I'm not terribly concerned it's going to collapse the fishery," said Leonard, the DNR biologist.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Some of the shrimpers who spoke to The AJC were wary of the proposed connection between 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and black gill in Georgia. They speculated the prevalence of the parasite could be caused by chemical runoff, contamination from farmed shrimp or 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  to the ecology of the sounds since they were barred from trawling there in the late '70s.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But they also say they have seen 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  that seem to fit a broader pattern.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I've noticed, over the past 10 years, that it seems like the best shrimp production is occurring further and further north," said Bill Harris, who owns two 75-foot trawlers and manages a dock in Townsend. "Our falls have been faltering and the black gill settling in, while further north that traditionally had no white shrimp season at all are just logging these phenomenal landings."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Pat Mathews, a third-generation shrimper, said when he first started seeing black gill, it would only appear in white shrimp in late summer. Then it began showing up in brown shrimp in June. This year, he found it in roe shrimp as early as May.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "It definitely flourishes when the water temperature peaks," said Mathews. "If this black gill goes away, we're liable to all be doing good. Back like it used to be."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But to Frischer, the microbiologist, black gill is more likely a harbinger of things to come.
