\f3\fs20 \cf0 Atlanta isn't home to any icebergs at risk of melting. It's not on the coast, where rising sea levels can flood communities. And while summers in the city are hot, Atlanta is far from becoming a dry desertscape.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But the impacts of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  are likely to still put long-term stress on metro Atlanta, scientists, officials and activists said, one day after The New York Times published a report that predicts rising temperatures nationwide and reduced rainfall in the southeastern United States.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The study, which had not been made public but was obtained by the Times, was conducted by researchers from 13 federal agencies and concluded that the average U.S. temperature is expected to rise. In the southeast, the report predicts, conditions are getting drier.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "We look at the science; we are aware of the trends that only seem to be worsening when it comes to the impacts of a warming 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," Stephanie Stuckey, the chief resilience officer for the City of Atlanta, said. "We're very aware of the drought and the increasing temperatures."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 An overwhelming majority of scientists agree that the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , and that humans are primarily responsible for global warming.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Even land-locked cities like Atlanta, Stuckey said, will witness the effects of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , specifically a water supply that could decrease over the next several years. At the same time, the city is also likely to face population growth as an indirect result of sea level rise, which can force coastal residents to move inward, she said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The report published Monday night "rings true to what we've seen in previous reports," said Marshall Shepherd, a meteorologist and the director of the Atmospheric Sciences program at the University of Georgia.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Different parts of the state are vulnerable to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in different ways, Shepherd said. Urban areas are more likely to see extreme heat and intense bursts of urban flooding, while southern parts of the state are more susceptible to drought, he said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Within the metro area, Stuckey's team is preparing a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  action strategy, which includes longterm solutions for increasing energy and water efficiency. The city hopes to build a water reservoir, install solar panels on public buildings and partner with the private sector to increase sustainability.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One area already seeing the impacts of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is the Chattahoochee River, which creeps across almost the entire state and provides water to about 4 million people.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is a real threat to river flow, and to rainfall, and to heat -- all factors that affect the river system," said Juliet Cohen, the executive director for Chattahoochee Riverkeeper. "That 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  will affect many aspects of the human and environmental experience. We know that they are occurring, scientists have documented them."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Less rainfall, which the recent federal report anticipates, would "aggravate an already contentious relationship between the various users of the river system," Cohen said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Rising temperatures can impact fish and wildlife, and flooding damages infrastructure, she said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Georgians have turned a closer eye to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in recent years, research suggests. Almost 70 percent of residents believe global warming is happening, and 55 percent said they are worried about global warming, according to a 2016 study by the Yale Program on 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Communication.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This weekend, outspoken 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  activist Al Gore is scheduled speak at the progressive Netroots Nation conference in downtown Atlanta. And next month, Chattahoochee Riverkeeper is hosting their first-ever conference on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . The Atlanta Journal-Constitution is one of the sponsors of that conference.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The report published by the Times raised eyebrows because the scientists' conclusions contradict statements made by President Trump and members of his administration, the newspaper noted. Trump announced in June that he will pull the U.S. out of the 2015 Paris 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Agreement, and Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Scott Pruitt has said he does not believe carbon dioxide emissions are a primary driver of global warming.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Actions by the federal government, however, have little impact on what Atlanta officials do to fight 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , Stuckey said. "I tend to focus on where I can actually have impact and where we have direct control," she said. "Our energies are directly spent on (asking), where can we as cities be really forward-thinking and innovative?" Mayor Kasim Reed, in conjunction with many mayors across the country, pledged to still uphold the city's commitment to the Paris accords. "All the cities jointly," Stuckey said, "are so much more powerful than a federal entity, because it's a global network."
