\f3\fs20 \cf0 Eight short years ago, when Al Gore ran for president, his views on global warming inspired widespread scoffing and jokes. The vice president was "Owl Gore" and "Nature Boy," or, as the first President Bush sometimes called him, "Ozone Man."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 However, as 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in the planet's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  have become more and more undeniable, the political 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  has slowly begun to 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  as well. Once-frozen attitudes are beginning to thaw; once-solid opposition to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science is finally beginning to melt. And maybe, just maybe, on this 38th anniversary of Earth Day, the time for real progress draws near.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It is notable, for example, that U.S. Sen. John McCain, the Republican nominee for president, accepts the reality of man-made global warming and the need to address it effectively. His campaign describes him as "a leader on the issue of global warming, with the courage to call the nation to action on an issue we can no longer afford to ignore." As McCain sees it, "Ignoring the problem reflects a 'liberal live-for-today' attitude unworthy of our great country."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And McCain is hardly alone. Newt Gingrich, the former Republican speaker of the House, has cut a TV spot with current Speaker Nancy Pelosi, urging investment in clean energy as a way to address 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Our country must take action to address 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," Gingrich says in the commercial. "If enough of us demand action from our leaders, we can spark the innovation we need."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 President Bush, an ex-oil man, also grudgingly acknowledges that the planet is heating, that mankind is driving much of that 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and that international action is required. Last week, he endorsed an approach that "will require commitments by all major economies to slow, stop, and eventually reverse the growth of greenhouse gas emissions," even if Bush's proposed timetable for that 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is impossibly slow.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Even Republican governors, including those in neighboring Florida and South Carolina, are advocating a 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in their party's approach to global warming. As Gov. Mark Sanford of South Carolina puts it, on the issue of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , Republicans "have conceded the high ground to those on the far left."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Of course, there are always those reluctant to accept an inconvenient truth, and Georgia Republicans too often are among them. While the rest of the world and much of their own party have come to grips with the reality of global warming, Republican legislators here in Georgia take a stubborn pride in their ignorance. While other states take steps to address the issue, Georgia legislators schedule "hearings" dominated by 
\f1\i\b \ul climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  deniers who long ago lost credibility elsewhere.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 While that reflects poorly on Georgia and the wisdom of its leadership, on a global scale it really doesn't matter much. The scientific debate on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and its causes is drawing to a close, as statements by McCain, Bush and other prominent Republicans demonstrate. Regardless of the outcome of this year's election, the next stage will be a political debate about how best to respond, not whether to respond at all.
\f0\fs24 \
