\f3\fs20 \cf0 NEW YORK--Exxon Mobil Corp. won Tuesday in a closely watched lawsuit over the costs of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , with a judge saying there was no proof the energy giant duped investors about the toll that regulations could take on its business.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 New York Attorney General Letitia James' office didn't prove the company made any material misstatements "that misled any reasonable investor," state judge Barry Ostrager wrote in dismissing the case. "Nothing in this opinion is intended to absolve Exxon Mobil from responsibility for contributing to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  through the emission of greenhouse gases," he added. "But Exxon Mobil is in the business of producing energy, and this is a securities fraud case, not a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  case."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Exxon Mobil hailed the ruling. "We provided our investors with accurate information on the risks of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," the Irving, Texas-based company said in a statement. "Lawsuits that waste millions of dollars of taxpayer money do nothing to advance meaningful actions that reduce the risks of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 James, however, said the case "laid out how Exxon made materially false, misleading and confusing representations to the American people about the company's response to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  regulations."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The oil giant never took seriously the severe economic impact that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  regulations would have on the company, contrary to what they were telling the public," the Democrat said in a statement. The suit sought an estimated $476 million to $1.6 billion in restitution to shareholders. It also was seen as something of a bellwether for how investors view energy companies' prospects in light of global warming and new regulations it's expected to spur.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The lawsuit accused Exxon Mobil of essentially keeping two sets of books -- telling the public that it was fully taking into account the costs of potential future 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  regulations in a warming world, while lowballing those costs behind the scenes as it made investment decisions and assessed the value of its oil and gas reserves. Scientists have warned that the world must cut emissions from the burning of fossil fuels to stave off the worst effects of warming.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The judge noted there was no testimony from any actual investors who claimed to have been deceived and called the lawsuit "hyperbolic."
\f0\fs24 \

