\f3\fs20 \cf0 Atlanta Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms addressed a U.S. Senate committee Wednesday about the city's efforts to combat 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bottoms was on a panel of five mayors who testified at the first meeting of the Senate Democrats' Special Committee on the 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Crisis.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The hearing was intended to showcase large cities' strategies to reduce carbon emissions and adapt to new challenges stemming from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . The mayors also discussed how the federal government can help their cities.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bottoms talked about several projects in Atlanta that she sees as key to combating 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone --now and in the future.Among them: the city's new reservoir and the new 280-acre park that Bottoms said will help "mitigate historic flood problems" in Northwest Atlanta.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bottoms' remarks also focused on the impact that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  has on Atlanta's most vulnerable populations.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One of the problems that come with rising temperatures is an increase in ground-level ozone, which aggravates asthma symptoms. This disproportionately affects African Americans, who are three times more likely to be hospitalized and die because of asthma compared to white people, the mayor said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "We see an average of 26,000 emergency room visits for asthma and wheezing in Atlanta every year, and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  will only make it worse," Bottoms said at the hearing, noting her own four children suffer from asthma.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bottoms was the only mayor of a Southern city and the only female mayor to testify at the hearing.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 She joined Mayor Kirk Cardwell of Honolulu;Mayor Melvin Carter of St. Paul, Minnesota; Mayor William Peduto of Pittsburgh; and Mayor Ted Wheeler of Portland, Oregon.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bottoms also noted the impact 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  will have on power bills. Low-in-come Atlanta residents already have the third-high-est energy burden in the nation, and higher temperatures will only worsen that, Bottoms said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bottoms said Atlanta would benefit from an expansion of the Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program. The program, run by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, provides grants to low-income people to help with the cost of energy bills.
