\f0\i0\b0\fs24 \ulnone \

\f3\fs20 We owe our standard of living today to advancements in science and should appreciate messages from scientists. Our past and future progress dealing with the pandemic hinges on understanding the virus and developing solutions to its spread. Perhaps scientists will have a vaccine to save us this year. Scientists have also been warning of the dire consequences of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  unless we wean ourselves of fossil fuels and convert to renewable energies. Just as with the pandemic, scientists and industry have busily been developing clean energy solutions such that now they are cheaper than fossil fuels without even counting the effects of pollution and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , and the consequent remediation the fossil fuel industry owes us. Our dilemma is confronting the creeping effects of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  without having the sense of urgency of a pandemic. We need to pass the Carbon Fee and Dividend Act to encourage our transition to clean energy. It won't affect your wallet, but it will save our future.
