\f3\fs20 \cf0 The warning is pretty stark.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Unless we figure out what to do about reduced (water) supply and increased demand, I don't think there's any way to support Atlanta's growth," says Aris Georgakakos, director of the Georgia Water Resources Institute at Georgia Tech. "There's no way."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Georgakakos has studied Georgia's water resources for 30 years, and over that time has seen significant 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Between 1960 and 2009, he says, the amount of water flowing through the Appalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basin, which provides most of the water for metro Atlanta, has fallen by more than 20 percent.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And the culprit is 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The Southeast is getting drier, that's for sure," Georgakakos says. "There will be more intensive droughts, more long-term droughts. It has very serious implications, because the flow in the rivers is going to decline and we've already seen a decline in all the river basins in Georgia."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Georgakakos was a lead author of the water-resources chapter in the recently released National 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Assessment, a congressionally mandated study of the current and projected impact of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  on the United States. He is also involved in water issues in the Middle East, Africa, China and Europe. And he expresses little doubt that the 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  documented here and around the globe are being driven by mankind.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "
\f1\i\b \ul Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is happening," he says. "Ask yourself questions: Why do you think the insurance companies left Miami? You think because they're crazy people? They're leaving Miami because the sea is rising."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Without the effect of carbon and other emissions, you cannot explain how the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  at a high rate like this, a rate that has not been historically documented before," he says. "The natural phenomenon of solar 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and volcanic eruptions --- the stuff that actually affect the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  --- cannot explain the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  of the last 50 years."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 However, given the scale of 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  that he sees looming, Georgakakos also advocates setting aside the politically sticky issue of causality to concentrate on preparation and adaptation. For example, if 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  continues on its current path, flow in the ACF river basin is projected to drop by another 20 percent over the next 50 years. Part of that decline will be due to increased withdrawals, but 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  will have by far the bigger impact.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The problem is that if you wait two or three decades to do something, it is too late. The 50 years that we're talking about are now. The time to do something is now. The adaptation and mitigation have to begin now so we can reduce these kinds of impacts."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I wish I could get the governor and the state of Georgia to start looking at 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  as part of the planning process," he says, a tone of urgency rising in his voice. "Other states are far ahead of us. Florida, New York, California are far ahead of us, because they are already seeing its effects."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I just don't know how this is going to work out with these folks in the end," he says, his tone shifting from the urgent to the wistful.
