\f3\fs20 \cf0 Faithful called to be stewards of Creation
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The weather is our nation's favorite topic for small talk, and there's been plenty to discuss in this year of record-setting temperatures, wildfires, drought and storms. Yet when it comes to talking about the larger, long-term implications of the weather (that is, 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ), our leaders shy away from the issue.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A recent poll by the Yale University Project on 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Communication found that 61 percent of undecided voters said they see global warming as an "important issue." Yet, during the recent presidential debate on domestic policy, this topic was not mentioned.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Politicians may shy away from talking about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , but as people of faith, we cannot be silent. The member congregations of Georgia Interfaith Power & Light recognize that God calls us to be good stewards of Creation, and to care for our neighbors. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is a moral issue. We can't ignore the growing reality of weather havoc, and we owe it to our kids to act now for their future.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Rather than arguing choices between good jobs and cleaner energy, we should celebrate that Americans have the ingenuity to successfully address the challenges of our 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . We invite all faith communities to join us in this vital work.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 ALEXIS CHASE, EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR, GEORGIA INTERFAITH POWER & LIGHT
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 DROUGHT
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Recent rainy days need some love, too
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Why do local Atlanta radio and t.v. weather forecasters invariably describe dry, sunny days as a "10" on their scales, and give rainy days a much lower mark of quality? Certainly, they're aware of the awful drought of 2012, and in fact, they usually remark on how many inches of rainfall we're below average.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This year, as millions of Georgians (especially those in any agricultural industry) can attest, lack of adequate rainfall is a hurtful thing. The best weather days are like those we experienced recently - when it rained for about 24 hours continuously.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Weather folks, be a little happier when rain is in the forecast!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 RON LIPSITZ, SANDY SPRINGS
