\f3\fs20 \cf0 West's wildfires long studied and even predicted
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The late Stephen Schneider put forward some possible future scenarios in his 1989 book, "Global Warming." He wrote that California's biggest concern would be "the frequent episodes of smoky sky a constant reminder of the growing intensity and scale of wildfires," with early dry seasons and hot summers increasing the fire potential. Recent days and years have proved Schneider correct. Present-day studies from Stanford University confirm the growing risk of large, rapidly growing wildfires as a result of a warming 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Both Schneider and modern studies acknowledge the adverse effect of improper land-use management, but it is widely accepted the 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  plays a major role in exacerbating these deadly and costly disasters. Recently, Forbes magazine asked, "Is anybody listening? How much longer will we continue to ignore the impact of our continued refusal to do anything to mitigate the planet's long-standing 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  emergency?" Dr. Schneider would undoubtedly agree with everyone's frustration.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 DAVID GREENLAND, SANDY SPRINGS
